  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(15) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "All that are with me salute thee.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—It is uncertain where Paul was when he wrote this letter. “All that are with me” include those with him, journeying in his company. They are not named, because the individuals composing the immediate following of St. Paul would be likely to be well known to Titus.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Greet them that love us in the faith.—An inclusive greeting, embracing each member of the Cretan Church whose love to him (St. Paul) was based upon the common faith in the Lord Jesus. Greet all who love me, as the earnest preacher of their faith and mine.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Greet them that love us in the faith.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—An inclusive greeting, embracing each member of the Cretan Church whose love to him (St. Paul) was based upon the common faith in the Lord Jesus. Greet all who love me, as the earnest preacher of their faith and mine.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Amen.—The greater number of the ancient authorities omit “Amen.”",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Amen.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
