            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Greet them that love us in the faith",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] Rather: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "salute them that love us in faith",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ‘in faith,’ as ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Timothy 1:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ‘my true child in faith,’ i.e. spiritually, where see note. The phrase marks the gradual crystallising of the word ‘faith,’ somewhat as ‘our Christian friends’ has become a modern formula: cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Titus 1:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ‘in communion of faith.’",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Grace",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " be ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "with you all. Amen",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] The shortest form of the Benediction, the fullest being at the end of 2 Cor. ‘An inclusive benediction that comprehends the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "episcopus",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and those committed to his oversight, Titus and all the faithful in Crete.’ Bp Ellicott; who rejects the final ‘Amen,’ as at the end of both the letters to Timothy, though the ms. authority for it is stronger here, on the ground that accidental omission seems less probable than insertion. The end recalls the beginning; the Apostle, whose sphere of ministry was the faith and full knowledge of the Cretan Christians, prays for ‘grace’ to be with them ‘all.’",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The subscription given above has no sufficient authority; see note at end of 1 Tim.; and for ‘Macedonia’ note above, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Titus 3:12",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Titus 3:12",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The best supported subscription here is simply To Titus.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
